{"acm_portal":{"simpl.id":"680058546","location":"http:\/\/dl.acm.org\/citation.cfm?id=2002766&preflayout=flat","pages":"135-140","title":"Search in the lost sense of \"query\": question formulation in web search queries and its temporal changes","abstract":"Web search is an information-seeking activity. Often times, this amounts to a user seeking answers to a question. However, queries, which encode user's information need, are typically not expressed as full-length natural language sentences --- in particular, as questions. Rather, they consist of one or more text fragments. As humans become more search-engine-savvy, do natural-language questions still have a role to play in web search? Through a systematic, large-scale study, we find to our surprise that as time goes by, web users are more likely to use questions to express their search intent.","additional_locations":{"location":["http:\/\/portal.acm.org\/citation.cfm?id=2002766&preflayout=flat","http:\/\/dl.acm.org\/citation.cfm?id=2002766&preflayout=flat","http:\/\/portal.acm.org\/citation.cfm?id=2002766"]},"clippings":[{"text_clipping":{"context":"Search in the lost sense of \"query\": question formulation in web search queries and its temporal changes","text":"Search in the lost sense of \"query\": question formulation in web search queries and its temporal changes","acm_portal":{"simpl.ref":"680058546"}}}],"authors":{"author":[{"mm_name":"authors","location":"http:\/\/dl.acm.org\/author_page.cfm?id=81324492678","name":"Bo Pang","affiliations":{"acm_portal_institution_profile":[{"mm_name":"affiliations","location":"http:\/\/dl.acm.org\/inst_page.cfm?id=1028549&CFID=196319304&CFTOKEN=68985144","title":"Yahoo! Research, First Ave, Sunnyvale, CA"}]}},{"mm_name":"authors","location":"http:\/\/dl.acm.org\/author_page.cfm?id=81100382445","name":"Ravi Kumar","affiliations":{"acm_portal_institution_profile":[{"mm_name":"affiliations","location":"http:\/\/dl.acm.org\/inst_page.cfm?id=1028549&CFID=196319304&CFTOKEN=68